World of Warcraft Mythic Dungeon Representation Analysis

Joseph C. Bernstein

Every patch of World of Warcraft releases a new raid tier and season. Each expansion contains a range of dungeons that five people will enter and attempt to complete. There have been varying difficulties over the years, but more recently, it has been toned to normal, heroic, and mythic difficulties, with mythic containing a trial mode based on an affix and key system. The affixes rotate weekly, always alternating between extra dungeon boss health and damage, and extra non-boss enemy health and damage. To expand a bit more on the key system, after a dungeon is completed, a key to a random dungeon is dropped for all members. This key increases the difficulty of the next dungeon, scaling infinitely. Rewards are capped at +15, but the score reward is uncapped. Groups will try to push higher keys in an attempt to gain more score for the leaderboards.

Each dungeon group contains a tank, a healer, and 3 damage dealers. The focus of this document is to analyze damage dealer class performance and representation, and if possible, attempt to identify which types of classes have a history of success to determine which type of class to play going into the new WoW expansion: Dragonflight.

To start, let's look at the most recent season in the 9.2 patch of the expansion: Shadowlands. To do so, we have a number of options.

  1. Raider.io is a website that pulls from the warcraft api to compile comprehensive leaderboards for raid and dungeon rankings.
  2. Warcraftlogs is another site that takes in user generate combat logs and completes statistical analysis on individual and class performance, but Warcraftlogs is used primarily for raid encounters.
  3. Access the warcraft API directly from https://develop.battle.net/documentation/world-of-warcraft/game-data-apis. For this third option, you will need a Blizzard Dev account, which is easy to make, and an OAuth Access token from the Dev account. After making an account from the provided website, enter the client ID and client secret string to enable access to the API. The API's provided contain access to individual player look ups, Mythic Plus dungeon leaderboards by realm, specific dungeon content, and a plethora of other specific information access.

From raider.io we can pull each classes' spec performers over the 9.2 mythic dungeon season patch. The Score associated with each player is calculated based on the highest level completion (with a bonus to competions within the time limit) across all dungeons in the expansion. Each dungeon carries a high score, and the total player score value is aggregated across all available dungeons. In short, a higher score means higher average difficulty dungeon competions. From this report, we can upload the information into a CSV that is available in the github repository supporting this webpage here:https://github.com/jewjojo/jBernsteinCs320Final.

For access to the original data, please visit https://raider.io/ and https://raider.io/api#/, or use the blizzard Mythic Keystone Dungeon API. The blizzard API will return the leaderboards for each dungeon, including each player and class information. The same information is available on raider.io's leaderboard page, or mythic-plus/runs API lookup. With the lookup, one can search the top players manually, but the raider.io page is a quicker and cleaner alternative.

The data stored within the following table contains the top 10 players for each dps specialization for each class.

Before moving into the history of each class over the expansion, we have yet to address another major component within the data set. One of the key selling features of the Shadowlands expansion for World of Warcraft was the Covenant system. Each player selects a faction (covenant) to join, and along with cosmetic rewards, they gain two additional abilties. One is covenant specific, and the other is class and covenant specific. The consequence of this, many players imagined, would be that high end players would be forced to select the "best" covenant in terms of player power instead of the covenant that felt was the most interesting. The data from the raider.io contains covenant information for the top performers along with their scores. Let's take another look:

Clearly, only a few classes have any covenant diversity. Paladins and Monks only use one covenant, and for most specs, one covenant is a clear winner in popularity. In 9.0, the launch of Shadowlands, swapping covenants not only reset all progress in terms of power progression, but swapping back to a covenant one has left was time gated behind a two week waiting period. I would like to highlight the failure of the system in regards to allowing players to choose freely, indicating an imaginary balance between covenants for each class, but the mandated friction only compounds the issue of covenant imbalance.

Speaking of imbalance, let's focus back on dungeon performance across Shadowland's history. When choosing a class to play, most players end up playing one or two classes at most. This changes by season and expansion, but the ease of creating a new character varies, so the initial choice of what to play at the start does matter, so how did classes perform over the course of the expansion? Were players able to at some point feel value in their decision?

Let's compare all the spec performances, accounting for the difference in mean score through standardizing across a patch.

With all the knowledge we now have, the big question left is "Should I play melee or ranged dps in the new WoW expansion: Dragonflight?"

While of course everything here will be speculation, we can use past trends to find the specs that have a history of success over the course of expansions. Dungeons so far have always had "trash," which are enemies to kill in area of effect damage, and dungeons always have bosses with their own mechanics. Based on past performance over many dungeons and seasons, we can hope to predict some top classes that always find their way into the meta. The choice of melee or ranged can be used as a guide for developing a dungeon team composition, so this initial choice will end up being important for competitive groups.

Going into this experiment, we can state a null hypothesis of H0: Melee-Range = 0, or in comprehensible terms, there is no significant difference between melee and ranged.

To determine whether a spec is melee or range, we will train a model on the set over the residual IO scores across 9.0 and 9.2. The hope is that the model will be able to accurately predict melee or range for a spec based on IO performance, which will then tell us how much we can know about the classes through IO.

In [36]:
# Our Model
def meleeOrRangedModel(specName, marker, df, index):
    IoScore = df.at[index, 'Score']
    # Compare the spec's IO to the threshold of the melee or range marker to decide if the spec is melee or range
    score = 0
    if IoScore >= marker:
        return True
    else:
        return False
In [37]:
# Model can use either the melee or ranged threshold markers
def trainModel(df, melee):
    accuracyCounter = 0
    if melee == 0:
        for index, row in df.iterrows():
            # If correct prediction, increase accuracy tally
            specName = df.at[index, 'Spec']
            if meleeOrRangedModel(specName, rangedMark, df, index) == df.at[index, 'Melee']:
                accuracyCounter = accuracyCounter + 1
    else:
        for index, row in df.iterrows():
            # If correct prediction, increase accuracy tally
            specName = df.at[index, 'Spec']
            if meleeOrRangedModel(specName, meleeMark, df, index) == df.at[index, 'Melee']:
                accuracyCounter = accuracyCounter + 1               
    return (accuracyCounter / len(df.index)) * 100

We can understand a lot about the classes from the results of the three model trainings. The first set is trained soley on data from the start of Shadowlands. We can see that the melee performed below average compared to their ranged counterpart, while the opposite is true when the data is trained on the later patch of 9.2. This would indicate a shift in balance towards the end of the expansion, or at the very least, a shift in class popularity in the high end playerbase.

The model was terrible at identifying both melee and ranged classes correctly at the start of the Shadowlands expansion. Low detection would seem to suggest an imbalance amongst the classes, which holds up with our own analysis. Affliction Warlocks suffering all expansion, while Balance Druids take over for the 9.0 launch patch, along with certain melee classes excelling far beyond others (Windwalker Monks compared to Survival Hunters).

By the 9.2 patch, the model significantly improved at both melee and ranged detection (noting that melee is still 50/50 guess, but still an improvement), while ranged is at least a positive detection. This would suggest that overall melee specs became closer to each other, and the same for ranged. If one were to create a new character in 9.2, there is less of a punishing experience in choosing the "wrong" spec, at least within one's own melee or ranged bubble.

When looking at the scope of the entire expansion, melee spec's have a classification accuracy of 66.6%, while ranged are sub 60%. This seems to imply that across all melee specs, one can expect a consistent experience no matter the spec they choose. Ranged, with the 58.3%, is slightly more volatile.

Another feature of note is the Melee and Ranged average threshold for each data set. At launch, the melee dps had a below average IO score, sitting at about -0.22 compared to the other specs, while ranged dps were above average with 0.26 standardized IO. This reversed by the 9.2 patch, with melee slightly in the lead with 0.068, and ranged dps at -0.08. The gap had closed, and melee had slightly taken over. Overall, the game in 9.2 is in a much more balanced state. Melee are not ahead on average by much, compared to the drastic lead ranged had over melee in 9.0. We can even see over all the data from 9.0 and 9.2 together than melee took the lead over the course of the entire expansion.

This would seem to suggest that it is better to select a melee spec to play in Dragonflight, however this analysis is not entirely complete. Some ranged dps specs, such as Destruction or Demonology warlock held up well over the course of the entire expansion. Taking a further look into each spec's history may yield more specific information if the player has a deeper thought in mind over which class to play, but on average over Shadowlands, both melee and ranged have had their time to shine. Going into Dragonflight, melee specs would be a safer bet for high end success, but there exist a number of likely ranged specs that will dominate. Ranged would seem to be likely to dominate the early patch, but for a consistent experience, melee would hold solid. However, for your own sake, dear reader, do not play Affliction Warlock.
